## Common Issues & Solutions

### Issue 1: Custom Field Value Cannot Be An Array Error

**Symptom:** When fetching a task and immediately PUTting it back with the same JSON payload, API returns error: "custom_fields: Value cannot be an array: []"

**Cause:** API asymmetry - GET requests return custom fields as an array of objects, but PUT/POST requests expect custom fields as a flat object mapping field GIDs to values. This is a known API design issue.

**Solution:**
```javascript
// âŒ DON'T: Use custom_fields directly from GET response
const task = await tasksApi.getTask(taskGid);
await tasksApi.updateTask(taskGid, { data: task.data }); // ERROR!

// âœ… DO: Transform custom fields for PUT/POST
const task = await tasksApi.getTask(taskGid);
const transformedFields = {};

task.data.custom_fields.forEach(field => {
  // For enum fields, use the selected option's GID
  if (field.resource_subtype === 'enum' && field.enum_value) {
    transformedFields[field.gid] = field.enum_value.gid;
  }
  // For multi-enum, use array of option GIDs
  else if (field.resource_subtype === 'multi_enum' && field.multi_enum_values) {
    transformedFields[field.gid] = field.multi_enum_values.map(v => v.gid);
  }
  // For text fields
  else if (field.resource_subtype === 'text') {
    transformedFields[field.gid] = field.text_value;
  }
  // For number fields
  else if (field.resource_subtype === 'number') {
    transformedFields[field.gid] = field.number_value;
  }
  // For date fields
  else if (field.resource_subtype === 'date') {
    transformedFields[field.gid] = field.date_value;
  }
});

await tasksApi.updateTask(taskGid, {
  data: {
    name: task.data.name,
    custom_fields: transformedFields // Use transformed object
  }
});
```

**Prevention:** Always transform custom fields when updating tasks. Create a utility function to handle the transformation automatically.

**Source:** https://forum.asana.com/t/api-error-custom-fields-value-cannot-be-an-array/76309

---

### Issue 2: Rate Limit 429 Errors

**Symptom:** Receiving "429 Too Many Requests" responses with Retry-After header, especially during bulk operations or high-frequency webhook processing

**Cause:** Exceeding rate limits - 150 requests/minute for free domains, 1,500 requests/minute for paid domains. Cost-based limits can also trigger 429s for expensive queries (deeply nested subtasks, large project queries).

**Solution:**
```javascript
/**
 * Retry function with exponential backoff
 */
async function retryWithBackoff(apiCall, maxRetries = 3) {
  for (let attempt = 0; attempt < maxRetries; attempt++) {
    try {
      return await apiCall();
    } catch (error) {
      // Check if it's a rate limit error
      if (error.status === 429) {
        // Get retry delay from header (in seconds)
        const retryAfter = error.value?.retry_after || Math.pow(2, attempt);
        const delayMs = retryAfter * 1000;

        console.log(`â³ Rate limited. Retrying after ${retryAfter}s (attempt ${attempt + 1}/${maxRetries})`);

        // Wait before retrying
        await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, delayMs));

        // Last attempt?
        if (attempt === maxRetries - 1) {
          throw new Error('Max retries exceeded for rate limit');
        }

        continue; // Retry
      }

      // Not a rate limit error - throw immediately
      throw error;
    }
  }
}

// Usage
const task = await retryWithBackoff(() =>
  tasksApi.createTask({ data: { name: 'Test task', workspace: workspaceGid } })
);
```

**Optimization strategies:**
- Use opt_fields to fetch only needed fields
- Batch requests when possible
- Implement request queuing to stay under limits
- Cache frequently accessed data (workspaces, projects, custom field definitions)
- Use webhooks instead of polling

**Prevention:** Monitor your rate limit usage and optimize expensive queries before hitting production load.

**Source:** https://developers.asana.com/docs/rate-limits

