### Issue 7: Deeply Nested Subtasks Cause Timeouts

**Symptom:** API requests for tasks with many levels of subtasks (5+ levels deep) timeout or return 500 errors. Cost-based rate limits trigger even with low request volume.

**Cause:** Asana's API performs graph traversal when fetching tasks with subtasks. Deep nesting creates exponential complexity, consuming significant computational resources.

**Solution:**
```javascript
// âŒ DON'T: Fetch tasks with deep subtask hierarchies
const task = await tasksApi.getTask(taskGid, {
  opt_fields: 'name,subtasks.name,subtasks.subtasks.name' // Expensive!
});

// âœ… DO: Fetch tasks without subtasks initially
const task = await tasksApi.getTask(taskGid, {
  opt_fields: 'name,completed,assignee.name' // Fast
});

// âœ… DO: Fetch subtasks separately in batches if needed
if (task.data.num_subtasks > 0) {
  const subtasksResponse = await tasksApi.getSubtasksForTask(taskGid, {
    opt_fields: 'name,completed',
    limit: 50 // Paginate for large numbers
  });

  const subtasks = subtasksResponse.data;
}

// âœ… DO: Flatten hierarchies in your data model
// Instead of 10 levels of subtasks, use sections or projects
```

**Prevention:** Limit subtask nesting to 2-3 levels maximum. Use project sections or separate tasks for complex workflows. Paginate subtask fetching for tasks with 50+ subtasks.

**Source:** https://developers.asana.com/docs/rate-limits

