### 3. Creative Automations

**Ideas discovered from research:**

#### 1. Automated Sprint Planning
**Description:** Automatically organize bug reports and feature requests into sprint projects based on priority, estimated effort, and team capacity.

**Implementation:**
- Run daily cron job to analyze backlog
- Calculate "sprint score" for each task (priority Ã— effort Ã· dependencies)
- Auto-assign highest-scoring tasks to next sprint project
- Balance workload across team members
- Notify team of sprint assignments via Slack

```javascript
async function autoSprintPlanning() {
  // Fetch backlog tasks
  const backlog = await tasksApi.getTasks({
    project: BACKLOG_PROJECT_GID,
    completed_since: 'now',
    opt_fields: 'name,custom_fields,assignee'
  });

  // Score each task
  const scoredTasks = backlog.data.map(task => ({
    task,
    score: calculateSprintScore(task)
  })).sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score);

  // Add top 20 to next sprint
  const sprintTasks = scoredTasks.slice(0, 20);

  for (const { task } of sprintTasks) {
    await tasksApi.addProjectForTask(task.gid, {
      data: { project: NEXT_SPRINT_PROJECT_GID }
    });
  }

  // Notify team
  await postToSlack(`ðŸš€ Sprint ${getNextSprintNumber()} planned! ${sprintTasks.length} tasks added.`);
}
```

#### 2. Customer Feedback Pipeline
**Description:** Automatically create Asana tasks from customer feedback collected across multiple channels (NPS surveys, app reviews, support tickets) and route to product team.

**Implementation:**
- Webhook receivers for each feedback channel
- Sentiment analysis to categorize feedback (positive/negative/neutral)
- Auto-tag with product area (using keyword matching)
- Weekly digest of feedback themes to product team

#### 3. QA Testing Workflow
**Description:** When developers mark bug tasks as "Ready for Testing", automatically create test task assigned to QA team with testing checklist.

**Implementation:**
- Webhook listens for tasks moved to "Ready for Testing" section
- Create new task "Test: [original bug name]"
- Copy reproduction steps from bug task
- Add testing checklist template
- Assign to QA rotation
- Link to original bug task as dependency

```javascript
async function createQATestTask(bugTaskGid) {
  // Fetch bug details
  const bugTask = await tasksApi.getTask(bugTaskGid, {
    opt_fields: 'name,notes,custom_fields'
  });

  // Create test task
  const testTask = await tasksApi.createTask({
    data: {
      name: `ðŸ§ª Test: ${bugTask.data.name}`,
      notes: `
Testing checklist for: ${bugTask.data.name}

**Original Bug:** https://app.asana.com/0/${bugTaskGid}

**Test Steps:**
- [ ] Verify bug is fixed in dev environment
- [ ] Test on multiple browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari)
- [ ] Test on mobile devices
- [ ] Verify no regression in related features
- [ ] Document any edge cases found

**Reproduction Steps from Bug Report:**
${bugTask.data.notes}
      `,
      projects: [QA_PROJECT_GID],
      assignee: getNextQATeamMember(), // Round-robin assignment
      dependencies: [bugTaskGid] // Can't complete test until bug is done
    }
  });

  return testTask.data;
}
```

#### 4. Release Notes Generator
**Description:** At the end of each sprint, automatically generate release notes from completed tasks and post to blog/changelog.

**Implementation:**
- Fetch all tasks completed in sprint
- Group by category (features, improvements, bug fixes)
- Extract customer-facing descriptions
- Generate markdown release notes
- Post to company blog or email newsletter

```javascript
async function generateReleaseNotes(sprintProjectGid) {
  // Fetch completed sprint tasks
  const tasks = await tasksApi.getTasksForProject(sprintProjectGid, {
    opt_fields: 'name,notes,custom_fields,completed_at',
    completed_since: 'now'
  });

  // Group by type
  const features = [];
  const improvements = [];
  const bugFixes = [];

  for (const task of tasks.data) {
    const typeField = task.custom_fields.find(f => f.name === 'Type');
    const type = typeField?.display_value;

    if (type === 'Feature') features.push(task);
    else if (type === 'Improvement') improvements.push(task);
    else if (type === 'Bug Fix') bugFixes.push(task);
  }

  // Generate markdown
  const releaseNotes = `
# Release Notes - ${new Date().toLocaleDateString()}

## ðŸŽ‰ New Features
${features.map(t => `- ${t.name}`).join('\n')}

## âš¡ Improvements
${improvements.map(t => `- ${t.name}`).join('\n')}

## ðŸ› Bug Fixes
${bugFixes.map(t => `- ${t.name}`).join('\n')}

---
**Total Changes:** ${tasks.data.length}
  `;

  return releaseNotes;
}
```

#### 5. AI-Powered Task Triage Bot
**Description:** Use Asana AI Studio to automatically categorize, prioritize, and assign incoming tasks based on content analysis.

**Implementation (using AI Studio):**
- AI reads task description
- Extracts key entities (product areas, customer segments, technical components)
- Suggests priority based on keywords ("urgent", "critical", "blocking")
- Recommends assignee based on expertise matching
- Posts analysis as comment on task

#### 6. Cross-Platform Content Approval Workflow
**Description:** For social media teams - automatically create approval tasks when new content is uploaded to Google Drive/Dropbox, route through stakeholders, and publish upon final approval.

**Implementation:**
- Google Drive webhook triggers when file added to "Pending Approval" folder
- Create Asana task with file preview
- Add approvers as followers
- Each approver completes subtask with their approval
- When all subtasks done, webhook triggers content publishing
- Move file to "Published" folder

#### 7. Time-Based Escalation
**Description:** Automatically escalate support tickets that haven't been responded to within SLA timeframe.

**Implementation:**
- Daily cron job checks all open support tickets
- Calculate time since creation
- If exceeds SLA (based on priority), add escalation comment
- Change priority to "Urgent"
- Assign to support manager
- Send notification to team lead

```javascript
async function checkSLAEscalations() {
  const now = Date.now();

  // SLA timeframes in hours
  const SLA_LIMITS = {
    'Urgent': 4,
    'High': 24,
    'Normal': 48,
    'Low': 72
  };

  // Fetch open tickets
  const tickets = await tasksApi.getTasks({
    project: SUPPORT_PROJECT_GID,
    completed_since: 'now',
    opt_fields: 'name,created_at,custom_fields,assignee'
  });

  for (const ticket of tickets.data) {
    const createdAt = new Date(ticket.created_at).getTime();
    const ageHours = (now - createdAt) / (1000 * 60 * 60);

    const priorityField = ticket.custom_fields.find(f => f.name === 'Priority');
    const priority = priorityField?.display_value || 'Normal';
    const slaLimit = SLA_LIMITS[priority];

    if (ageHours > slaLimit && !ticket.assignee) {
      // Escalate!
      await escalateTicket(ticket.gid, ageHours, slaLimit);
    }
  }
}

async function escalateTicket(taskGid, ageHours, slaLimit) {
  const storiesApi = new Asana.StoriesApi();

  // Add escalation comment
  await storiesApi.createStoryForTask(taskGid, {
    data: {
      text: `âš ï¸ **SLA VIOLATION** - This ticket has been open for ${Math.round(ageHours)} hours, exceeding the ${slaLimit} hour SLA. Escalating to support manager.`
    }
  });

  // Update task
  await tasksApi.updateTask(taskGid, {
    data: {
      assignee: SUPPORT_MANAGER_GID,
      custom_fields: {
        [PRIORITY_FIELD_GID]: URGENT_OPTION_GID
      }
    }
  });

  console.log(`ðŸš¨ Escalated ticket ${taskGid}`);
}
```

