## TL;DR
**You need a backend** - but since you already have Appwrite, just create a simple function that proxies ticket creation. Your frontend stays clean and secure.

**Yes! Absolutely!** You can add it to any existing Appwrite function. No need to create a new one.

## Quick Options:

### Option 1: Add to an Existing Utility Function
If you have a general-purpose function (like `EmailHandler` or any utility function), just add a new handler:

```javascript
// functions/EmailHandler/src/main.js (or whatever function you choose)

import { Client } from 'node-appwrite';
const Asana = require('asana');

export default async ({ req, res, log, error }) => {
  const action = req.headers['x-action'] || 'send-email'; // Route by header

  // Existing email handler
  if (action === 'send-email') {
    // ... your existing email code
  }

  // NEW: Asana ticket handler
  if (action === 'create-asana-ticket') {
    const { subject, description, userEmail } = JSON.parse(req.body);

    const client = Asana.ApiClient.instance;
    const token = client.authentications['token'];
    token.accessToken = process.env.ASANA_PAT;

    const tasksApi = new Asana.TasksApi();

    try {
      const task = await tasksApi.createTask({
        data: {
          name: `Support: ${subject}`,
          notes: `${description}\n\nFrom: ${userEmail}`,
          projects: [process.env.ASANA_SUPPORT_PROJECT_GID]
        }
      });

      return res.json({ success: true, ticketId: task.gid });
    } catch (err) {
      error(err.message);
      return res.json({ success: false, error: err.message }, 500);
    }
  }
};
```

### Option 2: Add to Your Frontend API Routes (Even Better!)

If you're using **Astro API routes** (which you are), just create an endpoint:

```typescript
// src/pages/api/support/create-ticket.ts

import type { APIRoute } from 'astro';
const Asana = require('asana');

export const POST: APIRoute = async ({ request }) => {
  const { subject, description, userEmail } = await request.json();

  const client = Asana.ApiClient.instance;
  const token = client.authentications['token'];
  token.accessToken = import.meta.env.ASANA_PAT; // Environment variable

  const tasksApi = new Asana.TasksApi();

  try {
    const task = await tasksApi.createTask({
      data: {
        name: `Support: ${subject}`,
        notes: `${description}\n\nFrom: ${userEmail}`,
        projects: [import.meta.env.ASANA_SUPPORT_PROJECT_GID]
      }
    });

    return new Response(JSON.stringify({ success: true, ticketId: task.gid }), {
      status: 200,
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }
    });
  } catch (error) {
    return new Response(JSON.stringify({ success: false, error: error.message }), {
      status: 500,
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }
    });
  }
};
```

**Then call it from your Vue component:**
```javascript
const response = await fetch('/api/support/create-ticket', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  body: JSON.stringify({ subject, description, userEmail })
});
```

## Recommendation: Use Astro API Route

Since you're already using Astro with SSR (Cloudflare Workers), **Option 2 is cleanest**:
- âœ… No new Appwrite function
- âœ… Keeps support logic with your frontend code
- âœ… Runs on Cloudflare Workers (fast, cheap)
- âœ… Easy to test locally with `npm run dev`

